# V1.17 Welle C — code review requirement on trust-root-protected surfaces.
#
# This file works WITH GitHub branch protection rules. CODEOWNERS by
# itself only auto-requests review; it does not REQUIRE the reviewer's
# approval for merge unless the branch protection rule "Require review
# from Code Owners" is enabled on the protected branch (master).
#
# Without the branch-protection setting, this file is documentary only
# (still useful — surfaces the right reviewer in the GitHub UI) but
# does NOT add an enforced gate. See docs/OPERATOR-RUNBOOK.md §14 for
# the operator-side branch-protection configuration that promotes this
# from documentary to enforcing.
#
# Why CODEOWNERS in addition to verify-trust-root-mutations.yml:
#   * Defence-in-depth. The workflow gate proves cryptographically that
#     a commit modifying the trust root is signed by an allowed key —
#     i.e. it answers "did a maintainer sign this?". CODEOWNERS adds a
#     human review requirement: "did a SECOND maintainer audit this?"
#     A PAT compromise typically gets the attacker exactly one
#     authenticated identity; two-maintainer review forces them to
#     compromise two independent identities to merge a malicious change
#     to the trust root.
#   * Surfaces the right reviewer in the GitHub UI even without
#     branch-protection enforcement. A maintainer browsing PRs sees the
#     trust-root surface flagged.
#
# Format: <path-glob> <space> <@user-or-team>
# GitHub uses last-match-wins semantics: a later line overrides an
# earlier matching line for the same path. Order matters.

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Trust-root surfaces (V1.17 Welle B + Welle C).
#
# Mirror of PROTECTED_SURFACE in tools/verify-trust-root-mutations.sh.
# Any change to one list should be reflected in the other; the test
# harness asserts the lists agree.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

